Thank God St. Paul isn’t here to attend to some chores. Otherwise I’d have writer’s cramp from proofreading the master’s masterful words. And then more timber inspectors will mix up these dried planks. Continue reading →

St. Paul says in the Sunday Epistle: “Brethren: Christ suffered in the flesh. Those who are dead to sin ought not to sin.” (1 Peter 4:1)

A lot of people suffer in the flesh. To be an alcoholic is to suffer in the flesh. If my older sister Mary Alice were alive, she’d tell stories about my father. When he got drunk every night and passed out from the pain, she and my mother had to lift him into the bed. When he blacked out, he’d kill the plants by putting out smokes. But the drunk guy Ardi was spiritually dead, so he and I didn’t know anything we hurt or killed were alive. Aquinas says those who are dead to the Ten Commandments do not know they sin against them. That’s why the Muslim man who killed that French priest didn’t know he was slaying Father Jacques Hamel. In both cases, something else was controlling the people. In Mass Wednesday morning, there was no death, no anticipatory lull or uneasiness or joking, a serious atmosphere bookended by the solemn,
